															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fieldstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1436137); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1436137&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182119" alt="fieldstone" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1436137)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fieldstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1436137); return false;" >fieldstone</a></span> <span class="odate time_1506049072 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Sep 2017 02:57</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3599210">
									

<p>Thanks for commenting -</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;that's&nbsp;just,&nbsp;like,&nbsp;your&nbsp;opinion,&nbsp;man</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;JK&nbsp;I&nbsp;really&nbsp;appreciate&nbsp;it</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I can get the dissonance being off-putting. Part of it comes from originally wanting this to be more of a character study and ending up at straightforward sci-fi/horror. Part of it is style choices I'm still getting the hang of &#8212; even in the context of detraction I'm still proud to see &quot;dream-like&quot; used to describe something I've written, and I gave little description of the characters and environments to keep them sketchy, so the reader can fill them in. But in hindsight it wouldn't have hurt to give some kind of visual signifier to everybody, like mentioning Evelyn wears glasses or describing her appearance as &quot;sharp-edged.&quot;</p>
<p>I definitely want the story to be more than just the surface, but the challenge for me is doing that quickly; I've been writing on the assumption that other people read the site like I do, a few minutes at a time throughout the day, and trying to make stuff that can be delivered in that framework. I got some feedback on this one that it would have been OK to make it a little longer, and in the future I plan to try taking things a bit slower so the characters have more time to develop and the reader has more time to enjoy the ride.</p>
<p>There are some plot points that don't really stand up to intense scrutiny &#8212; Ken venting to Mo the way he does, the power going out in the middle of their surgery &#8212; but those are things I tend to let slide for the sake of getting to the cool stuff without being bogged down. I'm an adamant defender of handwaving for the sake of entertainment, and just hope that in those cases the content is interesting enough that the reader lets me get away with it.</p>
<p>I'm bummed that you didn't enjoy the read, but even so, I still sort of like seeing the characters described as vague. I was going for a trippy, dreamlike experience, and feel like I nailed it, so I'm glad I had the opportunity to hear from somebody it didn't work for. Some of that missing 25% will probably fill in as I experiment/relearn a little (I wrote Ethics a really long time ago, so not counting SCP-3661 this is actually the first piece of creative writing I've finished in almost 2 years), so I hope you'll keep checking out the stuff that comes next to see how it develops.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

